Economics editor Thandeka Gqubule and SAfm current affairs producer Krivani Pillay have testified on orders they were given at the SABC. CAPE TOWN - Top South African Broadcasting Cooperation (SABC) journalists say the board and Parliament failed them when they took a stand against editorial decisions and policy changes by Hlaudi Motsoeneng.Economics editor Thandeka Gqubule and SAfm current affairs producer Krivani Pillay have been testifying before the parliamentary inquiry into the fitness of the SABC board to hold office.They are among the so-called SABC 8 who challenged Motsoeneng and were fired but then reinstated after a labour court battle.Pillay did not mince her words during her testimony. Parliament let us down, the board let us down, the minister let us down, our acting group CEO at the time Jimi Matthews let us down. All these people sold out journalists and sold out journalism. Gqubule described being taken to a meeting with former board chair Ellen Tshabalala and then Transnet CEO Brian Molefe who complained about questions put to him by SABC presenter Frances Heard.Gqubule also says they were pressured not to report that President Jacob Zuma crashed the rand when he axed former Finance Minister Nhlanhla Nene last December.(Edited by Winnie Theletsane)